Files for user management
=========================
/etc/passwd              # Stores basic user information (username, UID, GID, home dir, shell)

/etc/shadow              # Stores encrypted passwords & password aging info

/etc/group               # Stores group information (group name, GID, members)

/etc/gshadow             # Stores secure group info (encrypted group passwords, admins)

/etc/login.defs          # Defines default user settings (UID range, password policy)  #max days, min days, warn days

/etc/default/useradd     # Stores default values for user creation (shell, home dir)

/etc/skel                # Template directory for new users (default files copied to home directory of each new user)

/etc/sudoers             # Controls sudo access (who can run commands as root)

/home/username   # User home directory (personal files, configs)

/var/spool/mail/username   # Stores local mail for user

/etc/security/pwquality.conf   # Defines password complexity rules (length, characters, retry limits)

/etc/nologin                  # Prevents non-root users from logging into the system

~/.bashrc                     # User-specific shell config (aliases, environment variables, functions)

/etc/bashrc                   # System-wide bash configuration for all users

~/.bash_profile              # Executes on user login (sets environment, calls .bashrc)

/etc/profile                 # System-wide login configuration (applies to all users)

/etc/profile.d/              # Directory containing additional system-wide scripts

~/.bash_logout               # Executes commands when user logs out

~/.bash_history              # Stores history of executed commands for the user

