🐧 /etc/security/limits.conf

/etc/security/limits.conf is used to define resource limits for users and groups, such as number of open files, processes, and memory usage, 
helping to prevent system overload in multi-user environments.It controls how much system resources a user or service can consume, which is 
critical in production servers to ensure stability and avoid performance issues.

The configuration follows the format:         domain, type, item, value, where

domain   specifies the target (user, group using @group, or * for all users),
type     defines whether the limit is soft (temporary, adjustable by user) or hard (maximum enforced limit),
item     represents the resource (like nofile for open files, nproc for processes, cpu, memlock, etc.),value is the numeric limit.

Soft limits can be increased by users up to the hard limit, while hard limits cannot be exceeded and act as a strict ceiling,
which is an important interview concept.

Common real-world configurations include setting high nofile limits for web servers or databases to handle large numbers of 
concurrent connections, and limiting nproc to prevent fork bombs or excessive process creation.
These limits are enforced through PAM (Pluggable Authentication Modules), so for the configuration to work properly, 
the pam_limits.so module must be enabled in files like /etc/pam.d/system-auth or /etc/pam.d/common-session.
Changes made in this file apply only after the user logs out and logs back in, and in many production scenarios, 
services managed by systemd may override these limits, requiring configuration at the service level instead.
A commonly asked interview scenario is when limits are not applied, in which case you should check PAM configuration, 
user session reload, and systemd overrides.

